column3: Aristotle through the text comes up with his definition of what an idea tragedy is. One major element he describes is that it must "excite pity and fear".  Aristotle states and centers all of his other arguments around the tragedy actually producing fear or pity. For example, further down the text he states 'it neither satisfies the moral sense nor calls forth pity or fear." Another element that is described by Aristotle is that main character must have a change of fortune. Aristotle states that "...the spectacle of a virtous man brought from prosperity to adversity..." and says that the character "whose misfortune is brought about not by vice or depraviry, but by some error of judgement or frailty." Aristotle believed that the character needed to have a change of fortune which he believed should be from good to bad and it needed to be because of himself. Another element expressed by Aristotle is that tragedies should have a bad or unhappy ending. He states "Hence they are in error who censure Euripides just because he follows this principle in his plays, many of which end unhappily. It is, as we have said, the right ending." He believed that ideal tragedies should end unhappily, excite fear and pity, and have a change of fortune.
column4: Sure, here is the reworded passage:  Aristotle's definition of an idea tragedy is that it must evoke both fear and pity. He explains that a tragedy must affect the audience's sense of pity, adding that it must be a means of eliciting fear or, in other words, evoking a strong sense of terror or dread. Furthermore, Aristotle emphasized the importance of the character's suffering. He believed that the tragedy should revolve around the negative impact of an unjust or unlucky plot on the character's well-being. Finally, Aristotle argued that tragedies should have a tragic and unhappy ending, one that generates a sense of pity and fear in the audience. column3: One element of an ideal tragedy, according to Aristotle, is that the change of fortune of the main character should not go from bad to good, but instead, good to bad. He believes that the plays that have a bad ending for the main character are the most tragic in effect. Another element Aristotle thinks is important is having a main character that is not either a full-on villain or completely virtuous. This is because he thinks the downfall of a viruous man would simply shock the audience, while the downfall of a villain would satisfy the morals of the audience, but not cause them to feel pity or fear. The last element is that the main character's turn of fate shouldn't be brought about by immoral behavior, but instead by a great error or frailty. If a man's turn of fate was brought about through purely immoral reasons, the audience might think that he deserves it and not feel any pity for him.
column4: Aristotle believed an ideal tragic play should depict the main character's fortunes going from good to bad, not the other way around. He considered plays with tragic endings for the main character to be the most effective. The main character's journey should be one that goes through ups and downs, but the main character should not be portrayed as a villain or a hero. The main character's downfall should be caused by a terrible error or weakness, not by immoral behavior. The audience should feel that the main character's suffering is authentic and that they deserve compassion and pity.

column3: The Third Wave, a five-day experiment conducted by Ron Jones, was created for the history teacher to help his students understand how people in horrific historical events had followed the crowd in the wake of terrible things. He started the experiemnt small, by inviting students to join a movement title. 'The Third Wave", which aimed to bring down democracy. The movement stared out small in his classroom, by having kids pratice proper seating and abide by strict rules with him as their leader. Jones noticed that as the week went on, students had "a supreme sense of discipline and community" (CommonLit Staff) and even followed the Nazi-like salute Jones had made up. By the third day, the movement had tons of students involved all of whom showed, "a drastic improvment in academic skills and tremendous motivation" (CommonLit Staff). All members were issued a member card and given a specific task/assignment to honor the movement. As members started to learn how to recruit more people, membership increased to over 200 students. They asked questions in three words or less and prefaced all their statments with "Mr.Jones". By the experiment's fourth day, Jones saw an alarming amount of loyalty and dedication to the movement. So much, that he knew he had to shut it down, before it got out of control. To reveal that the whole movement had been an experiment, Jones convinced his students that a presidential candidate of the nationally-recognized movement was publicly announcing it's existence on T.V., and ordered them all to a noon rally on Friday. When the students got to the rally, all they saw was a blank screen. Jones revealed that they had been part of an experiment to show how quickly people will join a group to prove their superiorety over others or have a sense of community no matter the type of community. He also explained how people will excuse any actions as contribution to the movement or classify it for "the name of the state's honor" (CommonLit Staff). He had to shut the experiment down because the movement was getting ot of control and people were involving themselves into something that they knew little about. As people started to gain a false sense of confidence in the movement, they excused weird and controlled behaviors in the name of the movement.
column4: Sure. Here is the rewritten passage:  The Third Wave experiment was a five-day initiative designed by Ron Jones to engage students and foster a sense of unity and community during challenging historical times. Initially, Jones created a small movement, focusing on simple classroom regulations and adherence to strict rules. As the experiment unfolded, students displayed a heightened sense of discipline and teamwork, mirroring the qualities of the Nazi salute Jones made. By the third day, the movement had attracted a substantial number of students. They showcased impressive academic improvements and an eagerness to contribute, as they received personalized task cards to fulfill. This initiative ignited an overwhelming surge, with members reaching over 200, demonstrating the movement's captivating influence.  Inspired by the experiment's success, Jones orchestrated a grand rally on Friday, where students were instructed to assemble in the school assembly hall. The purpose? To showcase their dedication and highlight the spontaneity of the movement. However, the rally ended with an unsettling revelation as the blank screens displayed on the big screen served as a stark reminder of the experiment's futility. Jones explained that the purpose of the event was to reveal the true essence of the movement – it was an attempt to demonstrate the transformative power of unity and community.  Ultimately, Jones had to terminate the Third Wave initiative due to the potential for misdirection and misuse. To maintain control and prevent an uncontrollable surge, he ensured that participants were well-informed and maintained strict control over their actions, essentially exposing them to the dangers of extreme group dynamics.

column3: Three elements of an ideal tragedy are simple concepts. One element of a perfect tragedy would be a complex plan. It should have many layers to the plot, and make you feel many emotions (like sadness, anger, pity). Another element would be that the issue is on its own, and there are no other conflicts in the way. A third element that Aristotle says makes a perfect tragedy is the change of fortune. It should flip the script, and instead be from bad to good, end up from good to bad.

column3: In the system of government the classes were like a pyramid. The lower classes at the bottom and the higher classes at the top.  At the top is the "gods".
